<paragraph id="8BD06455FFA4FFD0FF4EF8E8FAB369BD" blockId="1.[151,1436,1796,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">
Galileo &amp; Martins (2006) described 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F1FD6FFA4FFD0FDE0F8E8FD6D6927" box="[569,754,1796,1821]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Lycidola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="popeba">
<emphasis id="B91BB847FFA4FFD0FDE0F8E8FD6D6927" box="[569,754,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">Lycidola popeba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a single male from Costa Rica. In doing so they commented that each elytron has three distinct carinae but failed to comment on the prosternal process. We observe that each elytron (
<figureCitation id="135478D0FFA4FFD0FEF2F8A0FEE6695E" box="[299,377,1868,1893]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 14. 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[205,1410,202,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[201,1417,196,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 14. 1 – 12, Elytral apex (odd numbers) and ventral side of the prothorax (even numbers): 1 – 2, Lycidola batesi, female; 3 – 4, L. expansa, male; 5 – 6, L. flavofasciata, female; 7 – 8, L. simulatrix, female; 9 – 10, Apeba barauna, paratype female; 11 – 12, A. togata, female. 13 – 14, Lycidola popeba, holotype male: 13, dorsal habitus; 14, ventral habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/438884/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) has only two distinct, complete carinae, with the third and innermost only moderately distinct at basal third, becoming even less so toward apex. Additionally, the prosternal process (
<figureCitation id="135478D0FFA4FFD0FBF4F883FBE369B2" box="[1069,1148,1903,1928]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 14. 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[205,1410,202,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[201,1417,196,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 14. 1 – 12, Elytral apex (odd numbers) and ventral side of the prothorax (even numbers): 1 – 2, Lycidola batesi, female; 3 – 4, L. expansa, male; 5 – 6, L. flavofasciata, female; 7 – 8, L. simulatrix, female; 9 – 10, Apeba barauna, paratype female; 11 – 12, A. togata, female. 13 – 14, Lycidola popeba, holotype male: 13, dorsal habitus; 14, ventral habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/438884/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) is very narrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37537DEFFA4FFD0FF1EF878FDC269CE" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD06455FFA4FFD0FF1EF878FDC269CE" blockId="1.[151,1436,1796,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">
Following the concept of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F1FD6FFA4FFD0FE31F878FDD76997" box="[488,584,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Lycidola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91BB847FFA4FFD0FE31F878FDD76997" box="[488,584,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">Lycidola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFE19A4FFA4FFD0FDACF878FC3B6996" author="Martins" box="[629,932,1940,1965]" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1991 a) Subdivisao do genero Lycidola Thomson, 1864 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae, Hemilophini). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 35 (3), 553 - 565." type="journal article" year="1991" yearSuffix="a">Martins &amp; Galileo (1991a)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F1FD6FFA4FFD0FC69F879FBBE6997" box="[944,1057,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Lycidola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="popeba">
<emphasis id="B91BB847FFA4FFD0FC69F879FBBE6997" box="[944,1057,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">L. popeba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should not have been included in this genus, since it does not have four carinae on each elytron and the prosternal process is narrow. Accordingly, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F1FD6FFA4FFD0FF4EF830FECE69CF" box="[151,337,2012,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Lycidola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="popeba">
<emphasis id="B91BB847FFA4FFD0FF4EF830FECE69CF" box="[151,337,2012,2037]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">Lycidola popeba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F1FD6FFA4FFD0FDD6F830FDC969CF" box="[527,598,2012,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Apeba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="446" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91BB847FFA4FFD0FDD6F830FDC969CF" box="[527,598,2012,2037]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="446">Apeba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
